article.description:
On a night when Memphis started its
third-string point guard and its leading scorer was limited to
seven points, the Grizzlies still defeated the top team in the
Atlantic Division.
article.headline: Third-string guard Watson scores career-high 21
article.linkText: Nets come out flat in road loss to Grizzlies
article.story:
MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- On a night when Memphis started its third-string point guard and its leading scorer was limited to seven points, the Grizzlies still defeated the top team in the Atlantic Division.
 
Watson
Earl Watson, starting because of injuries and illness, scored a career-high 21 points and handed out six assists Wednesday night to lead the Grizzlies to a 97-90 victory over the sluggish New Jersey Nets. Jason Williams came down with the flu before the game on a day when Memphis put reserve point guard Brevin Knight on the injured list with a sprained wrist, pushing Watson into the starter's role. "I saw this as a chance for me to play and have this team win," said Watson, a second-year player out of UCLA. "It was an opportunity for me to get better as a player. "I believe in myself a lot. I have a lot of confidence in what I can do because I put in the work. I just came out knowing good things were going to happen." Watson hit his first four shots to build that confidence. His final two free throws with 13.1 seconds remaining gave the Grizzlies a seven-point lead. The Grizzlies snapped a seven-game losing streak, while New Jersey dropped its second road game in as many nights. "We weren't ready to play, and it showed," Nets coach Byron Scott said. "I'm upset, but I'm not going to panic. ... When we started to play, it was too late. We gave them too much cushion." Wesley Person added 14 points for Memphis, while Lorenzen Wright and Drew Gooden had 11 each. Pau Gasol, the Grizzlies' leading scorer, took only eight shots for his seven points. Jason Kidd led New Jersey with 28 points, including 11 in the fourth period. The Nets cut the lead to one point twice in the second half, but could never overtake Memphis. Kenyon Martin had 15 points for New Jersey, and Kerry Kittles added 14. Watson connected on six of 12 shots from the field and all six free throws as Memphis won its first home game since Jan. 6. He also had eight rebounds and four steals. "To come out without Brevin and Jason against one of the best point guards in the league was big for us," said Memphis forward Shane Battier, who played point guard when Watson was out of the game. "It was no surprise to me. (Watson) puts in his work probably more than anyone else on this team. He was ready, and he is really a professional about his job." New Jersey shot poorly from the start, hitting only one of its first 11 shots and five of its first 23 from the field. The Nets shot 39 percent for the night. "We didn't guard. We didn't shoot. We really didn't do anything well," Martin said. Memphis built a 19-point lead in the first half and could have done better if it had not matched the Nets' nine turnovers. New Jersey cut the lead to eight before trailing 46-36 at the break. But in the third quarter, Memphis' offense sputtered and New Jersey steadily cut into the advantage, trailing 63-60 at the end of the third quarter. The Nets got closer early in the fourth quarter, cutting it to 63-62, but Memphis was able to hold on. "It was our ballgame, we just could not get over that first-half hump," Kidd said. "We came out in the first half and were flat shooting the ball. The game is four quarters, and we came back. We just lost." Game notes
The Grizzlies activated guard Michael Dickerson before the game and placed Knight on the injured reserve list with a sprained wrist. Dickerson didn't play. ... The Nets' eight first-quarter points were a franchise low for the opening stanza. The previous low was nine against the Pacers in 1989. The eight points also tied a Grizzlies' franchise low for points allowed in a quarter. ... Watson's previous career high was 17 points on Nov. 23 against Washington. ... New Jersey forward Richard Jefferson, third in the league in shooting at 52.9 percent, was 2-for-7. ... The Nets had won three straight in the series. They still hold a 9-4 advantage all-time.
